Hello,

I started using libGDX less than a week ago, so excuse me if this is not really an issue, but I think I found a bug.

I was reading the Scene2D tutorial about Actors, and playing out with the classes I created a simple scenario with an Image inside a Group. The issue I found was that if I use scale() on the Group, the image is not drawn into the screen.

Toying a little more I think I found the issue, and it is on the draw() method in the Group class. Inside applyTransform() is setting the transformation matrix of the batch again, and later in resetTransform() it is restored again. Shouldn't the transform matrix be scaled up on down, but using the same instance? To prove my theory I extended the Group class and it works. This is my code:

```
public class MyGroup extends Group {

    @Override
    public void draw(SpriteBatch batch, float parentAlpha) {
        // Instead of using super.draw(batch, parentAlpha);

        float scaleX = getScaleX();
        float scaleY = getScaleY();
        float scaleZ = 0;
        float rotation = getRotation();

        // Instead of if (transform) applyTransform(batch, computeTransform());
        if (isTransform()) {
            batch.getTransformMatrix().scale(scaleX, scaleY, scaleZ);
            // Do in some way... batch.getTransformMatrix().rotate(rotation);
        }

        // This is original
        drawChildren(batch, parentAlpha);

        // Instead of if (transform) resetTransform(batch);
        if (isTransform()) {
            batch.getTransformMatrix().scale(-scaleX, -scaleY, -scaleZ);
            // Do in some way... batch.getTransformMatrix().rotate(-rotation);
        }
    }

}
```

PS: Looking more into it I saw that using scale() in Group actually has no purpose, because the boundaries of the Group don't prevent the children to be drawn outside, but I guess this is a bug anyways. Shouldn't the children be drawn only inside the Group boundaries and be clipped if anything is drawn outside?

